<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Overview of Issues</TI>
<P>1. At issue is the ruling issued by the Honourable Mr. Justice Mahar, dated October 30<SUP>st</SUP>, 2014. Justice Mahar granted the Respondent's application and set aside the Appellants' decision to deny payment of a rebate of taxes paid on petroleum products purchased by the Respondent. The Appellant had denied the rebate on the grounds that the Respondent had failed to meet the statutory deadline for application set out in Section 8 (4.1 of the <EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM> (&ldquo;the Regulations&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. Justice Mahar held that the Appellant erred in its interpretation of Section 8 (4.1) of the Regulations. He held that the application deadline of March 31<SUP>st</SUP> applies only to fuel which is both bought into Nunavut <EM>and</EM> consumed in the previous calendar year. Justice Mahar further held that the Appellant was prevented from applying the deadline in Section 8(4.1) by application of the doctrine of promissory estoppel because it failed to take steps to inform the Respondent of a change to the regulatory deadline for applications.</P>
<P>3. The Appellant states that Justice Mahar's determination that it is prevented from applying the March 31<SUP>st</SUP> deadline to the Respondent's fuel tax application because of the operation of promissory estoppel is incorrect at law.</P>
<P>4. This Appeal raises an issue that is of central importance, both to the legal system as a whole, and to the Appellant in particular. The key core issue is whether the doctrine of promissory estoppel can act so as to prevent a government from relying on a statutory provision. The circumstances of this case do not give rise to the necessary elements of promissory estoppel, and that, even if estoppel could be demonstrated, it cannot serve to overcome a rule set out in statute.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Statement of Facts</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>i.</EM></N><TI><EM>Introduction</EM></TI>
<P>5. The Respondent is engaged in mineral extraction in Nunavut and has entered into a Development Partnership Agreement (DPA) with the Appellant and is therefore eligible to apply for a rebate under Section 5 of the <EM>Regulations</EM>.</P>
<P>6. Between 2006 and 2012, The Respondent submitted seven applications for fuel tax rebates, two of which were wholly or partially denied because of missed deadlines. The Respondent has received $9.3 million in tax rebates between 2009 and 2014.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Daniel Young, Sworn on October 25, 2013</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 82.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>7. Under Subsection 8(4.1) of the <EM>Regulations</EM>, a company that applies for a fuel tax rebate under Section 5 must submit the application by no later than March 31<SUP>st</SUP> in the year immediately subsequent to the year in which the fuel was purchased in or brought into Nunavut.</P>
<P>8. On June 7, 2013, the Appellant received two applications from the Respondent, in which it sought a rebate of taxes paid on fuel purchased in 2012. The applications were post-marked May 23, 2013. The Applications included receipts showing that in June, July, and October 2012 AEM had purchased some 47,266,562 litres of diesel oil from Woodward's Oil Limited, and had paid tax on all of the petroleum products at the lowest rate of 3.1 cents per litre.
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, P15</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. On July 12, 2013, the Appellant denied the Respondent's application for a fuel tax rebate on the grounds that it had not been submitted by the regulatory deadline of March 31<SUP>st</SUP>, 2013.
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, P47</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>10. The Respondent sought judicial review of the Appellant's denial of the rebate. In aide of its application, the Respondent argued that Section 8(4.1) did not apply to it, and that, if it did apply, then the deadline for application will be March 31<SUP>st</SUP>, 2014, not March 31<SUP>st</SUP>, 2013. It also argued that, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the Appellant was prohibited from applying the March 31<SUP>st</SUP> deadline by operation of the doctrine of promissory estoppel.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>ii.</EM></N><TI><EM>The Fuel Tax Regime in Nunavut</EM></TI>
<P>11. In Nunavut, as in other jurisdictions, fuel is taxed at varying rates depending on the purpose for which the fuel is used. These rates are set out in Section 2 of the <EM>Petroleum Products Tax Act</EM> (&ldquo;PPTA&rdquo;). The difference in tax rates based on various uses ranges from 0% tax for petroleum products used for home heating, to 17% for gasoline purchased on the highway system and used for purposes other than aviation. In most cases, this tax is payable on a prescribed amount that is deemed to be the price per litre, and not on the actual price per litre of petroleum products.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Petroleum Products Tax Act</EM> (Nunavut), R.S.N.W.T. (Nu) 1988, c. P-5 (&ldquo;<EM>PPTA</EM>&rdquo;), Ss. 2 (1)&mdash;2(7).</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 1]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. The fuel used by the Respondent in its operations falls under Subsections 2(1)(e) and (f) of the PPTA, meaning that the rate of tax is based on a prescribed taxable price per litre. The taxable price per litre is prescribed in the Regulations, and is currently set at 62.9 cents per litre, which means that the tax rates applicable to the Respondent are as follows:
<P1>i. in the case of diesel oil used in a motor vehicle, 9.1 cents per litre; and</P1>
<P1>ii. in the case of any other petroleum products, 3.1 cents per litre.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Petroleum Products Tax Regulations</EM>, R.R.N.W.T. 1990, c.P-3, s. 12(3).</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 2]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>PPTA</EM>, s. 2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 1]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. Registered fuel importers can purchase fuel outside Nunavut and bring it into the territory without paying taxes on it until it is used. Importers submit monthly returns, setting out the quantity of fuel used, the purpose for which it was used, and the amount of taxes owing.
<P1><BOLD><EM>PPTA</EM>, s. 4(1).</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 1]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. Those who do not import fuel and instead purchase it from an importer must pay taxes up front, before the fuel has been used. The vendor then remits the tax to the Minister.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>iii.</EM></N><TI><EM>The Fuel Tax Rebate Program</EM></TI>
<P>15. The Fuel Tax Rebate Program (&ldquo;the Program&rdquo;) was introduced in 2006 through the promulgation of Regulations under the PPTA. Section 23 of the PPTA gives the Minister the right to make regulations granting rebates of tax or any portion of tax to any person eligible for a rebate and prescribing the proof to be provided on application for exemption or rebate.
<P1><BOLD><EM>PPTA, s. 23</EM></BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 1]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. The Program rebates territorial taxes to eligible individuals and companies who use fuel for qualified activities, including harvesting, quarrying for carving stone, outfitting, mineral exploration, and mining development, extraction or reclamation.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>, Nu Reg. 012-2006, ss. 2&ndash;5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 3]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Daniel Young</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 81</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. Companies engaged in mining extraction wishing to claim a rebate of fuel taxes must do so under Section 5 of the Regulations. Section 5 provides that a company engaged in mine development, extraction or reclamation activities is eligible to apply for a rebate of taxes paid on eligible petroleum products if it has entered into and is in compliance with a DPA:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>5.</N><SECP>A corporation incorporated or registered under the <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> that engages in a particular mine development, mine extraction or mine reclamation is eligible to apply for a tax rebate on eligible petroleum products used directly for the purposes of that mine development, mine extraction or mine reclamation if the corporation has entered into and is in compliance with a development partnership agreement with the Government of Nunavut.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>, Nu Reg. 012-2006, s. 2</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 3]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. The term &ldquo;eligible petroleum products&rdquo; is defined in the Regulations as &ldquo;petroleum products used in Nunavut in qualifying equipment and machinery&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>, Nu Reg. 012-2006, s. 1</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 3]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Section 8(4) of the Tax Rebate Regulations states that an application for a tax rebate must be submitted within one year after the petroleum products were purchased or brought into Nunavut.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>, Nu Reg. 012-2006, s. 8</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities Tab 3]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. In April 2012, the Executive Council approved amendments to the Regulations by means of Regulation R-008-2012. One of the changes was the addition of Section 8(4.1), which imposed a deadline of March 31st in respect of fuel tax rebate applications filed by companies under Section 5 of the Tax Rebate Regulations.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Daniel Young</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 82</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. Regulation R-008-2012 was published in the Nunavut Gazette on May 25, 2012, in accordance with the Statutory Instruments Act and the Public Printing Act. The Regulations were consolidated and an up to date version was posted by the Territorial Printer on the GN website on October 19, 2012.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Daniel Young</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 82</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Section 8(4.1) of the Tax Rebate Regulations applies only to those companies such as the Respondent, whose eligibility for the rebate flows from Section 5. It states that, despite subsection 8(4), an application made by a person referred to in Section 5 of the Regulations must be submitted on or before March 31st in respect of eligible petroleum products purchased in or brought into Nunavut in the preceding year.</P>
<P>23. The Respondent is a person referred to Section 5 of the Regulations.</P>
<P>24. In an affidavit submitted in aid of its application, the Respondent's Administrative Director testified that the Respondent did not meet the March 31st deadline for applying for the fuel tax rebate because it did not know about the deadline. She states that, in preparing and submitting its application for a fuel tax rebate, the Respondent used and relied upon 2009 Fuel Tax Rebate Guidelines found by Comptroller Valerie Drolet by means of an internet search using the search engine Google.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Manon Lessard, paras 47&ndash;50</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 8-9</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. Ms. Lessard has testified that, even if the Respondent had been aware of the changes to the deadline for application, it could not have submitted its application by March 31, 2013, because it had not completely used the fuel that it had purchased in 2012 until August 2013, and therefore could not have known how it would be used. However, AEM ultimately filed its rebate application in May, three months before the fuel was fully consumed.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Manon Lessard, para. 63</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I, at 11</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. According to Ms. Lessard, AEM started using the fuel it had imported in 2012 in August of that year. By December 2012, it had consumed 27,559, 007 litres of fuel, out of a total of 63,411,381 of fuel imported in 2012. The fuel had been totally consumed by August of the following year.
<P1><BOLD>Affidvit of Manon Lessard, at para. 63</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume 1, at 11</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Each of the rebate applications filed by AEM contains the following comment in the comments section:
<QUOTE><P>Consolidation of <EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM> (Current to October 19, 2012) was used to complete this form.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume 1, P14, P30</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. This Consolidation cited by the Respondent includes Subsection 8(4.1).</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;GROUNDS OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>29. The Appellant submits that the learned trial judge erred by:
<P1>a. concluding that the Appellant's actions amounted to a representation to the Respondent such that it was estopped from applying the regulatory deadline set out in Section 8 (4.1) of the Regulations; and</P1>
<P1>b. in concluding that the doctrine of promissory estoppel could overcome a statutory deadline.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;POINTS OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Standard of Review is correctness</TI>
<P>30. Where the Courts have already made a determination regarding the standard of review to be applied to a given question; the required analysis is deemed to have been performed and need not be repeated.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Net v Brunswick (Board of Management) v. Dunsmuir (&ldquo;Dunsmuir&rdquo;)</SOC><CITE>1 S.C.R. 190</CITE><PARANUM>57</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 4]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. At issue in this appeal is whether an equitable doctrine can serve to overcome the application of a statutory provision. As agreed by the parties and accepted by Justice Mahar, the standard of review in this matter is correctness.</P>
<P>32. Questions of law that are of central importance to the legal system and outside the adjudicator's specialized area of expertise will always attract a correctness standard. Courts must continue to substitute their own view of the correct answer where the question at issue is one of general law. These questions require uniform and consistent answers due to their impact on the administration of justice as a whole.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Toronto (City) v. CUPE Local 79</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 63</CITE><PARANUM>62</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 5]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Dunsmuir</EM>, supra, at para. 60.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Doctrine of Promissory Estoppel requires a clear and unambiguous representation</TI>
<P>33. The doctrine of promissory estoppel has been applied in rare circumstances in the public law context, predominantly in the criminal or strict liability context, where it has arisen under the guise of &ldquo;officially induced errors&rdquo;. However, the courts have held that, in the public law context, a clear and unambiguous statement by a public authority is required; actions or acquiescence will not ground a claim of promissory estoppel.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Immeubles Jacques Robitaille inc. v. Qu&ea;bec (City)</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 34</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2014] 1 SCR 784</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, (&ldquo;Robitaille&rdquo;), at para 19.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 6]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. In a recent judgment of the Supreme Court of Canada, Justice Wagner summarized the prerequisites for the establishment of promissory estoppel in the public law context as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[19] In the public law context, promissory estoppel requires proof of a clear and unambiguous promise made to a citizen by a public authority in order to induce the citizen to perform certain acts. In addition, the citizen must have relied on the promise and acted on it by changing his or her conduct (<CASEREF><SOC>Mount Sinai Hospital Center v. Quebec (Minister of Health and Social Services)</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 41 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2001] 2 S.C.R. 281</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Mount Sinai</EM>&rdquo;), at paras. 45-46, quoting <CASEREF><SOC>Maracle v. Travellers Indemnity Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>1991 CanLII 58</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1991] 2 S.C.R. 50</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; J.-P. Villaggi, <EM>L'Administration publique qu&ea;b&ea;coise et le processus d&ea;cisionnel: Des pouvoirs au contr&oc;le administratif et judiciaire</EM> (2005), at p. 329).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Ibid.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. In this case, Justice Mahar held that a government may be bound to act consistently with statements made to another party where that party has relied upon those statements. He canvassed the case law and determined that the Respondent had ordered its affairs in reliance upon the Appellant's Fuel Tax Guidelines.</P>
<P>36. Justice Mahar set out his reasons for finding that the Appellant's failure to update its Guidelines, coupled with its failure to advise the Respondent of the change to the Regulations, constituted a &ldquo;promise&rdquo; which effectively barred the Appellant from applying the Regulatory deadline.</P>
<P>37. Justice Mahar based his ruling on three key facts: the advent of the Internet, which he held, created a higher onus on the Appellant to ensure that the information it provides is kept up to date; the fact that only one taxpayer was affected by the regulatory change; the ongoing relationship between the Appellant and the Respondent; and the fact that the effort to contact the taxpayer directly and inform it of the change would have been minimal. He concluded that the combination of these factors constituted a &ldquo;promise&rdquo; by the Appellant not to make any changes to the regulatory regime without informing the Respondent:
<QUOTE><P>[85] The doctrine of promissory estoppel will be a rare and unusual remedy in tax cases, highly unusual when dealing with a taxpayer failing to follow specific statutory requirements. However, in this particular case, on these unusual facts, it is made out. The combined effect of the misguiding Guidelines, the less than helpful forms, and a reasonable reliance on the ongoing relationship between AEM and the Government leads to what is, in effect, a &ldquo;promise&rdquo; that the regime was continuing as it had before.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Appeal Book, Volume I F18</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. The Appellant submits that Justice Mahar's determination that the Appellant's failure to update its Guidelines or to contact the Respondent directly constituted a &ldquo;promise&rdquo; sufficient in nature to ground promissory estoppels in the public law context is incorrect. It quite simply cannot be reconciled with the vast weight of the common law that precedes it.</P>
<P>39. Inaction, acquiescence, or inadvertence will not ground promissory estoppels in the public law context. What is required is a clear and unambiguous statement by an enforcement body to a regulated entity or person. Neither the Appellant's failure to update its Guidelines, nor its failure to contact the Respondent and advise it of the change to the Regulations are insufficient to ground promissory estoppel.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Doctrine of Promissory Estoppel cannot serve to overcome a statutory deadline</TI>
<P>40. Even if the Appellant's failure to update its Guidelines or inform the Respondent of the statutory change were determined to constitute a clear and unambiguous promise, it still would not protect the Respondent from the application of the regulatory deadline. The basic premise that equitable doctrines cannot overcome the application of statutory provisions is well established. Justice Wagner confirmed the law in this regard in the Robitaille decision:
<QUOTE><P>[20] However, the doctrine of estoppel must yield in the public law context to an overriding public interest and may not be invoked to prevent the application of an express legislative provision (<EM>Mount Sinai</EM>, at para. 47; <CASEREF><SOC>St. Ann's Island Shooting and Fishing Club Ltd. v. The King</SOC><CITE>1950 CanLII 28</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1950] S.C.R. 211</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 220</PAGENUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>).</P>
<P>[21] Furthermore, although the doctrine of estoppel has been applied against public authorities in the past, the promises made by the representatives of the authorities in those cases were not unlawful, or were actually consistent with a statutory discretion (<CASEREF><SOC>Re MultiMalls Inc. and Minister of Transportation and Communications</SOC><YEAR>1976</YEAR><CITE>1976 CanLII 623</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>14 O.R. (2d) 49</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Sous-ministre du Revenu du Qu&ea;bec v. Transport Lessard (1976) Lt&ea;e</SOC><CITE>[1985] R.D.J. 502</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Aurchem Exploration Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>91 D.L.R. (4th) 710</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Kenora (Town) Hydro Electric Commission v. Vacationland Dairy Co-operative Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 105</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1994] 1 S.C.R. 80</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Robitaille</EM> Supra, at paras 20 - 21.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 6]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. At paragraph 30 of that same judgment, Justice Wagner clarified that, although the appeal was grounded in the penal law context, the principle is the same in the civil law context:
<QUOTE><P>[30] Nor, it should be added&mdash;although it is not necessary to do so to decide this appeal, which arises in a penal law context&mdash;can estoppel be raised as a defence in a civil proceeding relating to an express provision of a by-law in which a non-conforming use is at issue. <UNDER>The principle that estoppel cannot be raised in the face of an express legislative provision is valid both in the penal law context and in that of a civil proceeding</UNDER>.</P>
<P>(Emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Ibid., at para. 30</EM></BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. Estoppel has been invoked by the courts to stop the unfairness that can occur where one party tries to withdraw a promise made to a second party when the latter has reasonably relied on that promise.</P>
<P>43. In <CASEREF><SOC>Maracle v Travellers Indemnity Co</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court described the doctrine as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The principles of promissory estoppel are well settled. The party relying on the doctrine must establish that the other party has, by words or conduct, made a promise or assurance which was intended to affect their legal relationship and to be acted on. Furthermore, the representee must establish that, in reliance on the representation, he acted on it or in some way changed his position.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Marack v Travellers Indemnity Co.</SOC><CITE>[1991] 2 S.C.R. 50</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 7]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. However, the doctrine of estoppel has its limits, the most notable of which is that it cannot operate to countermand statute or regulation. This was made clear by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Minister of National Revenue v. Inland Industries Ltd</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Inland Industries&rdquo;). In that case, the Minister of Revenue approved a retroactive payment by a taxpayer into a pension fund, the benefits of which would go to the sole shareholder of the taxpayer. The monies were then invested by loaning them to affiliated companies at a significantly high interest rate. The affiliated companies, who were constantly in debt to the taxpayer, simply remitted the monies to the taxpayer. The Minister alleged that the pension fund was a sham; the investors were acting as an agent of the taxpayer, not for the pension fund, and that the monies never really went into the pension fund, and therefore ought to have been taxed. The taxpayer appealed. Among the grounds for appeal were that the Minister had approved the plan with full knowledge, on the advice of the Superintendent of Insurance (a government agent as well). The Supreme Court held that the Minister could not be bound by an approval given where the conditions of the law were not met:
<QUOTE><P>The difference between the wording of this memorandum and the wording of the actuarial certificate is quite substantial and it is somewhat surprising that, notwithstanding such advice, departmental approval was given to the payments on behalf of the Minister. However, it seems clear to me that the Minister cannot be bound by an approval given when the conditions prescribed by the law were not met.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Minister of National Revenue v. Inland Industries Ltd</SOC><CITE>[1974] S.C.R. 514</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 8]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. Inland Industries stands for the principle that: the doctrines of estoppel and considerations of fairness cannot operate to overcome clear provisions of law, meaning that where a statute says that a taxpayer does not qualify for a rebate, neither incorrect advice, nor confusing bulletins can operate to nullify the effect of the statute or regulation.
<P1><BOLD>Ibid.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. In <CASEREF><SOC>Irving Oil Ltd. v. R.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Federal Court stated that the doctrine of estoppel and fairness does not apply to when the core issue is whether a statute has been correctly applied. The decision has been summarized as follows:
<QUOTE><P>3. The doctrine of estoppel and fairness did not apply where the issue was one of the correct interpretation or application of a statute as opposed to a decision on rights or entitlement by a statutory authority, particularly as it was in the public interest to recover the overpayment. Moreover, it was too speculative to contemplate whether 10 Ltd. would have ordered its affairs differently and avoided the overpayment of compensation had the old formula not been used. Also, the method adopted was one suggested by 10 Ltd. and acquiesced in by the board, not the other way around. Finally, it was irrelevant that consumers might now have to pay more for 10 Ltd.'s products assuming they had been oversubsidized in the past.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Irving Oil Ltd. v. R</SOC><CITE>[1984] 1 F.C. 281</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2 Admin. L.R. 53</CITE><PARANUM>39&ndash;50</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 9]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. In <CASEREF><SOC>Nelson Consulting Services Ltd. v. R.</SOC></CASEREF>, a judgment of the Tax Court, the taxpayers made enquiries of agents of the Canada Revenue Agency as to how to file their taxes, and tried their best to comply with the Act, but still ended up with a $70,000 debt to the Minister for G.S.T. that they had failed to collect and remit. The Court, while sympathetic to the taxpayers, rightly concluded that bad advice from agents of the Minister could not relieve a taxpayer from the clear application of the law:
<QUOTE><P>5 Mr. and Mrs. Blinn, understandably, feel that they did everything that they could to comply with the law. This case certainly demonstrates the danger inherent in operating even a modest business in this country without the benefit of ongoing professional advice. I have no doubt that the Blinns had every intention of complying with the Act, and felt that they were being careful to do so. Unfortunately, their frequent inquiries of Revenue Canada are to no avail; <UNDER>I am bound by the decision of the Supreme Court of</UNDER> <UNDER>Canada in Inland Industries, which held that having relied upon bad advice from agents</UNDER> <UNDER>of the Minister cannot relieve a taxpayer from the application of the law</UNDER>. There is no ambiguity in the legislation; HST was exigible, and the Appellant failed to collect and remit it. The appeal must be dismissed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nelson Consulting Services Ltd. v. R.</SOC><CITE>[2002] G.S.T.C. 122</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2003 G.T.C. 506</CITE><PARANUM>5</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 10]</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>See also:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Woon v. Minister of National Revenue</SOC><CITE>[1950] C.T.C. 263</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>50 D.T.C. 871</CITE><PARANUM>17 - 18</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 11]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. In <CASEREF><SOC>Gemini Biochemical Research Ltd. v. R.</SOC></CASEREF>, a 1997 judgment of the Tax Court of Canada, the facts were almost identical to this case. The corporate taxpayer had been taken unawares by a change to the deadline for submission of materials related to a claim for a rebate of expenditures related to research. The taxpayer argued that, because the Guidelines for filing did not advert to the changed deadline, and because the Minister had not advised him of the change in the deadline, it ought not to be applied.</P>
<P>49. Justice Rowe responded to a taxpayer's arguments about the failure of the Guidelines to incorporate the new deadline as follows:
<QUOTE><P>They didn't have to. First of all, the very use of the word &ldquo;guideline&rdquo; is exactly indicative of what it is, it's a guideline. There's no requirement that your company be specifically put on a mailing list that Revenue Canada has to advise you when it's about to change the law and if you rely on waiting for changes in tax law to make its way into a guideline, you're going to do so at your peril, as was the case here, so there's no requirement in law that these kind of amendments&mdash;people are presumed to know and to keep abreast of this. The royal assent was, the Minister says, received on June 15th, 1994, and there was appropriate proclamation in the Canada Gazette. There must have been some information released by way of circular or a reference in the newspapers or Globe &amp; Mail or something, and the fact that it was not contained in the particular guideline is of absolutely no import or significance as a matter of law. If you've missed the deadline, you missed the deadline and I take it that you don't quarrel with the fact that the deadline for providing information regarding these expenditures was missed.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gemini Biochemical Research Ltd. v. R.</SOC><CITE>[1997] 3 C.T.C. 2664</CITE><PARANUM>6, 16</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>[Book of Authorities, Tab 12]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. In summary, the principle that neither Government Guidelines, nor poor advice by representatives of the Department, nor forms, nor any other kind of publication can serve to countermand a regulatory provision is well established in Canadian law.</P>
<P>51. So long as the provisions of the Act and Regulations have been properly applied, they will prevail over any advice given by agents of the Minister, as well as any written opinions, memos, or bulletins, notwithstanding that a taxpayer may have relied upon them in conducting their business.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;NATURE OF RELIEF DESIRED</TI>
<P>52. For all of the reasons the appellant respectfully requests that this Honourable Court allow the Appeal, set aside the decision of the Chambers Judge, and reverse lower Court's decision as it relates to that portion of the fuel to which the deadline in Section 8(4.1) was held to apply.</P>
<P>53. The Appellant further asks the Court to grant its costs in this matter.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted on June 26, 2015.</P>
