<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I. STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. Although the Appellant put in issue the entire judgment of Justice Mahar,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Amended Notice of Appeal</EM> (Appeal Book, March 20, 2015 (&ldquo;<BOLD>AB</BOLD>&rdquo;), Tab 8, Bates page F20).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the appeal raises only the application of the doctrine of promissory estoppel in the context of the government decision at issue.</P>
<P>2. The Appellant does not challenge the test His Honour chose to consider the doctrine. It only challenges the <EM>application</EM> of this test, i.e. His Honour's findings and determinations as to whether the test is met. This is reviewable on the deference standard of a palpable and overriding error. The Appellant's assertion that the correctness standard applies in the circumstances of this Honorable Court's review and that the Respondent is in agreement with this standard<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Appellant's Factum</EM>, paras. 31-32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> is inaccurate.</P>
<P>3. The decision at issue is the Appellant's denial of a tax rebate to the Respondent under the Nunavut Fuel Tax Rebate program (&ldquo;<BOLD>Program</BOLD>&rdquo;). Justice Mahar overturned the decision. His Honour found that the denial of a portion of the rebate was inconsistent with the statute, and that the Appellant committed an error in failing to consider and properly apply the statutory law. In overturning the decision on this point, Justice Mahar interpreted the statutory law. <EM>None</EM> of this interpretation and His Honour's corresponding findings is challenged by the Appellant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Appellant's Factum</EM>, filed June 26, 2015, para. 29 (&ldquo;Grounds of Appeal&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>4. With respect to another portion of the rebate, Justice Mahar found that although it was not refundable under the statute, it was returnable to the Respondent in equity, under the doctrine of promissory estoppel.</P>
<P>5. In challenging His Honour's application of the test, the Appellant rests its case on two arguments. It states that: (a) its actions did not constitute a promise on which the Respondent relied and acted upon; and, (b) His Honour's decision purports to trump an express statutory provision which it argues equity cannot displace.</P>
<P>6. With respect to point (a), Justice Mahar considered the applicable facts and found that the conduct of the parties satisfied the legal threshold, i.e. that the Appellant's actions constituted a promise and that the Respondent relied and acted upon this promise. The promise was found in numerous communications from the Appellant, on which the Respondent relied and based its tax rebate applications.</P>
<P>7. In relation to (b), His Honour, after considering the applicable law, expressly rejected that the statutory interpretation at issue played any role in the application of the doctrine in the circumstances of this case. He asked &ldquo;whether the Government acted fairly in applying the provisions of the statute&rdquo; towards the company.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Reasons for Judgment</EM>, para. 75 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F15).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> His Honour's inquiry was proper. In reviewing the Appellant's actions under the test of estoppel, Justice Mahar concluded that the Appellant's actions were &ldquo;taxation by ambush&rdquo; and thus, unfair towards the Respondent. The fairness of the Appellant's actions is a factual inquiry, and is therefore reviewable on the deference standard by this Court.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>REBATE</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>APPLICATIONS</TI>
<P>8. The Respondent, Agnico Eagle Mines Limited (&ldquo;<BOLD>AEM</BOLD>&rdquo;), submitted two applications for a fuel tax rebate to the Appellant on May 23, 2013. The applications were for the fuel that the Respondent purchased in June, July and October of 2012. The amount claimed in the applications represented the amount of taxes the Respondent claimed under the Nunavut Petroleum Product Tax Rebate program. The Respondent claimed the return of $1,465,263.42 in Application 1, and $494,576.05 in Application 2. The applications were for the purchases of 63,411,381 litres of fuel.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, paras. 21&ndash;23 and Exhibits D and E &ldquo;Applications&rdquo; (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 5, 33&ndash;66);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 1, 16&ndash;22 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F2, F5).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>9. The Respondent used approximately 2/3 of this fuel, 43,703,826 litres, in 2013. The balance, 19,707,555 litres, was used in 2012. All the purchased fuel at issue was consumed by the Respondent in Nunavut in the equipment and machinery that AEM used for its mining activities.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, paras. 30, 31, 33, 35&ndash;45 (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 6&ndash;8).</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 16&ndash;22 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F5).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>DENIAL</TI>
<P>10. The Appellant denied any tax rebate on the only ground that the Respondent missed the March 31 deadline found in section 8(4.1) of the <EM>Fuel Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>. The Appellant applied section 8(4.1) to the applications.
<P1><BOLD>Transcripts of Cross-Examination of D. Young (&ldquo;Transcripts&rdquo;), Q 73&ndash;89 pg 14&ndash;17&mdash;AB, Tab 5, Bates pages 143&ndash;146; Lessard Affidavit, para. 46 and Exhibit F (Letter to AEM from Daniel Young, July 12, 2013)&mdash;AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 8, 67&ndash;69;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 23 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F5).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>JUSTICE MAHAR'S DECISION</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>FUEL USED IN 2013</TI>
<P>11. Justice Mahar found that the rebate was allowable for the fuel used by the Respondent in 2013. All of that fuel was used and claimed within a year of purchase, consistent with the applicable statutory limitation period.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 86 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. Justice Mahar interpreted the law, and found that only section 8(4) applied to this fuel. Section 8(4.1) did not apply because this fuel was not used in the same calendar year it was purchased.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 86 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. In particular, His Honour interpreted the provisions at issue as follows:
<P1>a. For all Section 5 companies, all fuel must be used for a defined purpose and claimed within one year of being purchased or imported into Nunavut in order to qualify for a rebate pursuant to section 8(4).</P1>
<P1>b. For any &ldquo;eligible petroleum product&rdquo;, fuel <EM>used</EM> for such a defined purpose, must be claimed by March 31st following the calendar year of its purchase or import and use, pursuant to section 8(4.1).</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 88 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. In interpreting these provisions, Justice Mahar concluded that the <EM>use</EM> of petroleum was critical. The legislative language of purchase vs. use of petroleum in the interpretation of the sections was the parties' main controversial issue before His Honour.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 56-57, 61, 63, 64, 67 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F11&ndash;13).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The Appellant failed to consider the &ldquo;use&rdquo; component of the legislation, applied the law incorrectly, and therefore was wrong in denying the applications.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 63&ndash;67, 86 (Tab 7, AB, Bates pages F12-13, F18).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>FUEL USED IN 2012</TI>
<P>16. Justice Mahar found that the fuel used in 2012 was not refundable under the statute. However, given the facts of this case, His Honour concluded this fuel was refundable under the doctrine of promissory estoppel.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 87, 89 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. In reaching this conclusion, His Honour considered the test for public law promissory estoppel.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 70, 71 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F13-14).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. The Appellant relies on the same test in its submissions to this Court.
<P1><BOLD>Appellant's Factum, para. 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. In its submissions to this Honourable Court, the Appellant relies on the case law which His Honour considered and analyzed in applying the test to the facts of this matter.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 68&ndash;85 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F13&ndash;18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. The Appellant's conduct in this case, in His Honour's view, was &ldquo;even more troubling&rdquo; as compared to the facts in the other case law. He concluded that the Appellant's conduct towards the Respondent amounted to &ldquo;taxation by ambush.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 78&ndash;84 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F16&ndash;18).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. In conclusion, His Honour recognized that the promissory estoppel &ldquo;will be a rare and unusual remedy in tax cases, highly unusual when dealing with a taxpayer failing to follow specific statutory requirements. However, in this particular case, on these unusual facts, it is made out. The combined effect of the misguiding Guidelines, the less than helpful forms, and a reasonable reliance on the ongoing relationship between AEM and the Government leads to what is, in effect, a &ldquo;promise&rdquo; that the regime was continuing as it had before.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 85 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F18).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>SECTION 8(4.1)</TI>
<P>22. Section 8(4.1) is a new section. It was introduced in 2012.
<P1><BOLD>Transcripts, Q 9-10 pg 4 (AB, Tab 5, Bates page 133);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 9,10 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F3-4).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Section 8(4.1) was passed within a few months, soon after it was introduced. It was passed without notice to or consultation with industry stakeholders or the Respondent. The lack of any consultation with the Respondent occurred despite the fact that the Respondent was the only company that would be affected by this section. There was nothing preventing the Appellant from consulting with the Respondent. In fact, the parties work together as part of a Development Partnership Agreement whereby the Respondent makes important contributions to the people of the territory. For this reason, the Respondent was shocked when it learned of the new deadline after March 31, 2013, and amazed that no one in the Appellant's team alerted it to such a significant change.
<P1><BOLD>Transcripts, Q 220&ndash;239 pg 38&ndash;41, Q 209&ndash;219 pg 36&ndash;38 (AB, Tab 5, Bates pages 165&ndash;170); Lessard Affidavit, paras. 16, 58-59, 4&ndash;13 (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 2&ndash;4, 10-11);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 5, 9&ndash;11, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F2&ndash;4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>COMMUNICATIONS WITH THE APPELLANT</TI>
<P>24. In preparation of its applications over the years, the Respondent has relied on the Appellant's instructions and guidelines, including those published in 2006 and 2009 as further described below, which the Respondent considered official and authoritative sources, and used its best efforts and diligence to comply with them. In addition, on occasion the Respondent's personnel had telephone and email exchanges with the personnel in the Appellant's Department of Finance in order to obtain additional information and clarifications. The Respondent also relied on the information obtained through these exchanges.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 48 (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 8-9);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 5&ndash;8, 11&ndash;15 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F2&ndash;4).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. In none of these exchanges did the Appellant mention the new deadline. The Respondent did not submit the applications at issue on or before March 31, 2013. As of March 31, 2013, the Respondent was not aware of the March 31 deadline.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, paras. 47&ndash;67 (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 8&ndash;12);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 5&ndash;8, 11&ndash;15, 75, 78&ndash;80, 82&ndash;85, 89 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F2&ndash;4, F15&ndash;19).</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI>2006 GUIDELINES</TI>
<P>26. Pursuant to the 2006 Guidelines, the Respondent's applications for tax rebates on fuel purchases, with the exception of the applications pertaining to purchases in 2011 and 2012, were based on periods dating from April 1 to March 31, and were submitted prior to March 31 of the following year.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 49 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 9);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 8, 12&ndash;14, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>2009 GUIDELINES</TI>
<P>27. As concerns the preparation of the rebate applications for the 2012 fuel purchases, the Respondent relied on the Appellant's <EM>Fuel Tax Rebate for Mining Development, Extraction and Reclamation Guidelines</EM> (Revised July, 2009) (&ldquo;<BOLD>2009 Guidelines</BOLD>&rdquo;), which, in the Appellant's words, have &ldquo;been prepared to assist [the claimant] in understanding the Fuel Tax Rebate for mining development, extraction and reclamation.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 50 and Exhibit G (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 9, 71&ndash;73);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 8, 12&ndash;14, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. The 2009 Guidelines provided instructions that applicants were required to file two (2) applications per year, the first for the period of April to September, with the application to be filed no later than September 30 of the following year, and the second for the period from October to March with the applications to be filed no later than March 31 of the following year, with the overriding instruction that in any event, rebate applications had to be submitted within one (1) year of the fuel purchases.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 51 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 9);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, <EM>ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. Therefore, based on fuel purchase dates of June, July and October in 2012, the Respondent believed that it had until June 2013 to file the first of its rebate applications (i.e. the rebate application pertaining to the fuel purchased in June and July 2012) and that the rebate application for the fuel purchased in October 2012 would not be due until October 2013.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 52 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 9-10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, <EM>ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>RESPONDENT'S PRACTICE</TI>
<P>30. The Respondent relied on the 2006 Guidelines and the 2009 Guidelines published by the Appellant's Department of Finance for instructions as to rebate applications under the Program.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 53 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 12, 31, 71 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. During all the years that the Respondent filed tax rebate applications under the Program, including the two (2) applications at issue, it had not come across, in any of the guidelines issued by the Government's Department of Finance and available on the Internet, any reference to the deadline of March 31 for filing rebate claim forms for fuel purchased in or brought into Nunavut in the preceding year.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 54 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 8, 12&ndash;14, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>APPELLANT'S FORMS</TI>
<P>32. Furthermore, a deadline of March 31 for filing rebate claim forms for fuel purchased in or brought into Nunavut in the preceding year does not appear in the instructions contained on the Appellant-issued rebate application forms outlining the requirements pertaining to the completion and filing of the application forms.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 55 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, <EM>ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. In reference to the applications at issue, the Respondent was guided by the statement found in the application form providing that &ldquo;No rebate can be claimed on fuel which was purchased or brought into Nunavut longer than one year prior to the application being submitted&rdquo;, which makes no reference to March 31.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 56 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 15 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F4).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. The Respondent used the information in the Appellant's guidelines and the application forms to make its fuel tax rebate claims and relied on that information. There was nothing in any of those documents to indicate any change to the deadline for the submission of the fuel tax rebate applications, nor any information that would alert the Respondent that a new date had become applicable. The Respondent believed that there had not been any change to the applicable deadline.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 57 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 10);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 8, 12&ndash;14, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. With respect to the Appellant's statements at paragraphs 27 and 28 of its factum that the applications at issue had referred to a consolidated version of the regulations, His Honour considered this fact and found it of no consequence.
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, para. 10 (AB, Tab 7, Bates page F4).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>2012 GUIDELINES</TI>
<P>36. After filing the applications at bar with the Appellant, the Respondent obtained a new version of the <EM>Fuel Tax Rebate for Mining Development, Extraction and Reclamation Guidelines</EM> updated by the Appellant as of May 2012.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 60 and Exhibit H &ldquo;2012 Guidelines&rdquo; (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 11, 75&ndash;79);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, paras. 8, 12&ndash;15, 31 (AB, Tab 7, Bates pages F3-4, F7).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. With respect to deadlines, the May 2012 version requires that fuel purchase invoices be attached to the rebate application and that invoices submitted must not be older than one (1) year. This is exactly what the Respondent did. This 2012 version was not used by AEM in preparing its rebate application; however, it would have made no difference as the guidelines are no different than the previous guidelines with respect to its applications and do not indicate the new March 31 deadline that had been adopted by the Appellant in May 2012.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 61 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 11);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, <EM>ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>NO REASON TO QUESTION APPELLANT'S MATERIALS</TI>
<P>38. Relying on the above stated material and following them in an effort to adhere to the filing requirements, the Respondent had no reason to disbelieve these or suspect they were in error, misleading or incomplete, or that the Respondent would be required to investigate on its own if there were any other requirements in addition or contrary to these instructions. Therefore, the Respondent did not search for any other sources to verify if there was any other information that would contradict the instructions issued by the Appellant's Department of Finance or indicate a major change in policy.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 62 (AB, Tab 3, Bates page 11);</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reasons for Judgment, <EM>ibid.</EM></BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. Even if the Respondent were subject to the law specifying the March 31 deadline, it was not in a position to file an application by March 31, 2013 stating the use of the fuel in question purchased during the preceding year. It did not know the use of the 2012 fuel purchases until August 2013 when the fuel had been consumed. It was only then that it knew the use of the fuel and whether it fell within the definition of an &ldquo;eligible&rdquo; petroleum product in accordance with the amended regulation and its definition section.
<P1><BOLD>Lessard Affidavit, para. 63 (AB, Tab 3, Bates pages 11-12).</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II. GROUNDS OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>40. The Respondent submits that Justice Mahar made no error in reaching the conclusion that the Appellant's actions were an actionable and reliable promise to the Respondent, and that equity required the Government to hold onto its promise, which permitted the application of the rebate as a result.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III. POINTS OF LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>PROMISSORY ESTOPPEL</TI>
<P>41. The test in public law of estoppel is fairness.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mount Sinai Hospital Center v. Quebec (Minister of Health and Social Services)</SOC><CITE>[2001] 2 S.C.R. 281</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;BOA&rdquo;), Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. Promissory estoppel is made where &ldquo;the other party has, by words or conduct, made a promise or assurance which was intended to affect their legal relationship and to be acted on. Furthermore, the representee must establish that, in reliance on the representation, he acted on it or in some way changed his position.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Maracle v. Travellers Indemnity Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>[1991] 2 S.C.R. 50</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Appellant's BOA, Tab 7;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Mount Sinai Hospital Center v. Quebec (Minister of Health and Social Services)</SOC><CITE>[2001] 2 S.C.R. 281</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. The promise must be unambiguous but could be inferred from circumstances.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Maracle v. Travellers Indemnity Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>[1991] 2 S.C.R. 50</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Appellant's BOA, Tab 7;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Mount Sinai Hospital Center v. Quebec (Minister of Health and Social Services)</SOC><CITE>[2001] 2 S.C.R. 281</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. Under this doctrine, a party is held to act consistently with statements they made to another party where that party has acted upon or relied upon such statements to guide their actions. The principle of estoppel is binding on the Crown.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Canada v. Langille</SOC><CITE>[1977] F.C.J. No. 46</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. Where promises made are consistent with the executives' statutory discretion, and are not contrary to the law, the doctrine of promissory estoppel applies. &ldquo;Protection of [entities] caught in the transition from a relaxed regime to a more strict regime&rdquo; is the key issue, and the main concern, in the judicial analysis of fairness / estoppel.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mount Sinai Hospital Center v. Quebec (Minister of Health and Social Services)</SOC><CITE>[2001] 2 S.C.R. 281</CITE><PARANUM>48-49</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 4; see also,</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Immeubles Jacques Robitaille inc. v. Qu&ea;bec (City)</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 784</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>(relying on</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Re Multi-Malls Inc. and Minister of Transportation and Communications</SOC><YEAR>1976</YEAR><CITE>14 O.R. (2d) 49</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Sousministre du Revenu du Qu&ea;bec v. Transport Lessard (1976) Lt&ea;e</SOC><CITE>[1985] R.D.J. 502</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Aurchem Exploration Ltd. v. Canada</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>91 D.L.R. (4th) 710</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Kenora (Town) Hydro Electric Commission v. Vacationland Dairy Co-operative Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1994] 1 S.C.R. 80</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>)&mdash;Appellant's BOA, Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. The Appellant enjoys this discretion under the applicable legislation. Tax rebate applications are made to the Minister of Finance, who shall pay the claimed tax rebate to the applicant if the application meets all requirements of the Regulations. In assessing the applications, the Minister reviews if the application is supported, including by various documentation of the claimant. For a better determination of whether the eligibility requirements for a tax rebate have been made, it is in the Minister's discretion to request additional information in connection with the application.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Tax Rebate Regulations</EM>, R-012-2006, ss. 7(1), 8(1), 8(3), 8(5), 8(6)&mdash;See Schedule A of this Factum.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. Justice Mahar fully considered this law in reaching his conclusions.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>STANDARD OF REVIEW</TI>
<P>48. Appeal courts are reluctant to interfere with findings of fact if there is evidence capable of supporting the decision and there is no palpable and overriding error.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Galaske v. O'Donnell</SOC><CITE>[1994] 1 S.C.R. 670</CITE><PAGENUM>at page 695</PAGENUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>49. The application of a legal standard to a set of facts is reviewed with deference, on the standard of palpable and overriding error.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>[2002] 2 S.C.R. 235</CITE><PARANUM>27, 29, 36, 37</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. Consistent with the above, &ldquo;once the correct test for estoppel is chosen, determinations as to whether the test is met (whether there has been an unequivocal representation and detrimental reliance) are questions of fact on which the [trier of fact] will be given deference.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>NCR Canada Ltd. (Re)</SOC><CITE>[2014] B.C.L.R.B.D. No. 152</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF><BOLD>(relying on</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Martin-Brower of Canada, Ltd. v. General Truck Drivers and Helpers Union, Local No. 31</SOC><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>112 D.L.R. (4th) 191</CITE><COURTJUR>B.C.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>), and 47&mdash;Respondent's BOA, Tab 5.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV. NATURE OF RELIEF DESIRED</TI>
<P>46. For the reasons set out above, the Respondent requests that the appeal be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 24<SUP>th</SUP> day of July, 2015.</P>
